{"hitCount": 1, "request": {"cursorMark": "*", "pageSize": 1, "queryString": "DOI:\"10.1007/s10856-012-4805-1\"", "resultType": "core", "sort": "", "synonym": false}, "resultList": {"result": [{"abstractText": "To improve the poor compatibility among different components of Drug-in-adhesive type patch, two novel plasters (Drug-in-fiber and Drug-in-adhesive/fiber) were developed based on ibuprofen (IBU)-loaded fiber mats. These fibrous mats were fabricated via electrospinning of cellulose acetate/poly(vinylpyrrolidone) composites in a binary solvent of N,N-dimethyl acetamide/acetone. Physical status studies suggested that Drug-in-fiber could inhibit IBU re-crystallization, but the active ingredients were released at a relatively slow rate due to the dual-resistance of fiber mat and adhesive matrix. To overcome this shortcoming, Drug-in-adhesive/fiber was designed by coupling medicated hydrophilic pressure sensitive adhesive and IBU-loaded fiber mat. This method endowed Drug-in-adhesive/fiber a fast IBU release rate and high permeated drug amount though simulative skins. This design separated enhancer from adhesive matrix, which guaranteed Drug-in-adhesive/fiber excellent adhesion forces. Hence, the plasters based on medicated fiber mats improved the compatibility among patch components.", "affiliation": "School of Chemical Engineering and Technology, Tianjin University, Tianjin, 300072, China.", "authMan": "N", "authorIdList": {"authorId": [{"type": "ORCID", "value": "0000-0001-7833-9715"}]}, "authorList": {"author": [{"authorAffiliationDetailsList": {"authorAffiliation": [{"affiliation": "School of Chemical Engineering and Technology, Tianjin University, Tianjin, 300072, China."}]}, "firstName": "Yongli", "fullName": "Shi Y", "initials": "Y", "lastName": "Shi"}, {"firstName": "Shuxin", "fullName": "Xu S", "initials": "S", "lastName": "Xu"}, {"firstName": "Anjie", "fullName": "Dong A", "initials": "A", "lastName": "Dong"}, {"authorId": {"type": "ORCID", "value": "000